1. UTF-16 encoding fundamentals in JavaScript
- JavaScript strings use UTF-16 encoding internally where each string element is a 16-bit code unit
- Unicode code points range from 0 to 0x10FFFF (1,114,111 decimal)
- Code points 0-65535 (0x0000-0xFFFF) fit in one UTF-16 code unit (Basic Multilingual Plane)
- Code points above 65535 require two UTF-16 code units called a surrogate pair
- High surrogates: 0xD800-0xDBFF, Low surrogates: 0xDC00-0xDFFF
- String.length returns count of UTF-16 code units, not Unicode code points or grapheme clusters

2. Character access methods and their behavior differences
- charAt(index) returns exactly one UTF-16 code unit as a string, empty string if out of bounds
- Bracket notation str[index] returns UTF-16 code unit as string, undefined if out of bounds
- charCodeAt(index) returns numeric value of UTF-16 code unit at position, NaN if out of bounds
- codePointAt(pos) returns full Unicode code point value (surrogate-pair-aware), undefined if out of bounds
- charAt and bracket notation may return lone surrogates (invalid Unicode characters)
- codePointAt automatically handles surrogate pairs and returns the complete code point

3. Surrogate pairs: detection, handling, and pitfalls
- Characters requiring surrogate pairs have string length of 2 despite being single glyphs
- Examples: Mathematical symbols ('𝒳'.length === 2), emoji ('😂'.length === 2), rare CJK characters
- Splitting strings at arbitrary positions can break surrogate pairs producing garbage characters
- Detection pattern: check if charCodeAt(i) is in range 0xD800-0xDBFF for high surrogate
- Safe iteration requires either codePointAt() method or spread operator [...str]
- Legacy methods like charAt() and charCodeAt() are not surrogate-pair-aware

4. Unicode normalization: forms and implementation
- Visually identical characters may have different Unicode representations
- Four normalization forms: NFC (Canonical Decomposition then Canonical Composition), NFD (Canonical Decomposition), NFKC (Compatibility Decomposition then Canonical Composition), NFKD (Compatibility Decomposition)
- String.prototype.normalize(form) method standardizes representation
- Default form is typically NFC when no parameter specified
- Use normalize() before string comparison when handling international text with combining characters
- Combining marks can be reordered and still produce visually identical results

5. Code unit vs code point vs grapheme cluster comparison
- Code unit: individual UTF-16 element (what charAt() returns)
- Code point: complete Unicode character value (what codePointAt() returns)  
- Grapheme cluster: user-perceived character including combining marks and ZWJ sequences
- For text processing choose appropriate unit based on requirements
- Use charAt() for simple ASCII text or when performance is critical
- Use codePointAt() or spread operator for full Unicode support
- Use Intl.Segmenter for grapheme cluster iteration (user-visible characters)

6. String iteration patterns for different Unicode units
- UTF-16 code unit iteration: for (let i = 0; i < str.length; i++) { str.charAt(i) }
- Unicode code point iteration: for (const codePoint of str) or [...str].forEach()
- Grapheme cluster iteration: new Intl.Segmenter(locale, {granularity: 'grapheme'}).segment(str)
- Converting to arrays: [...str] for code points, Array.from(str) for code points
- Manual surrogate pair handling: check high surrogate then increment by 2 if found

7. Edge cases and troubleshooting for international text
- String slice, substring, and substr may break surrogate pairs if not used carefully
- Length mismatches between visual characters and string.length property
- Comparison failures between visually identical normalized strings
- Performance implications of normalization and grapheme iteration
- Browser compatibility differences in Intl.Segmenter support
- Emoji sequences (ZWJ, variation selectors) affect grapheme boundaries

